{"title_page": "COVID-19 pandemic in England", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in England}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = COVID-19 pandemic in England\n| image           = Waitrose Supermarket - King's Road, London SW3 UK COVID-19 Lock down.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             =\n| caption         = Queue at a supermarket in London, each customer 2 meters from the next person; April 2020\n| map1 = COVID-19 outbreak England per capita cases map.svg\n| image2          = \n| places =\n| legend1 = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents by upper tier local authority area\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[England]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date =\n| origin = [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 131,932 (as of 7 May)<ref name=ArcGISUK>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the UK |website=coronavirus.data.gov.uk |access-date=1 May 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"theg_Coro\">{{Cite web| title = Coronavirus UK: how many confirmed cases are in your area?| last = Guti\u00e9rrez | first = Pablo| work = the Guardian| date = 27 March 2020| access-date = 27 March 2020| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/coronavirus-uk-how-many-confirmed-cases-are-in-your-area}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 27,432 (as of 7 May)<ref name=ArcGISUK/><ref name=\"bbc._Howm\">{{Cite web| title = How many confirmed cases are there in your area?| author = | work = BBC News| date = 2020-03-27| access-date = 27 March 2020| url = https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51768274}}</ref>\n| total_ili =\n| website = [https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus in England]\n}}\nThe [[COVID-19 pandemic]] was first confirmed to have spread to [[England]] with two cases among Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]] on 31 January 2020. The two main public bodies responsible for health in England are [[NHS England]] and [[Public Health England]]. NHS England oversees the budget, planning, delivery and day-to-day operation of the commissioning side of the NHS in England while PHE's mission is \"to protect and improve the nation\u2019s health and to address inequalities\".\n\nBy 7 May 2020, 27,008 people had died and there were 118,343 positive cases in England.<ref name=ArcGISUK/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== January 2020 ===\nOn 31 January, two members of a family of Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]], one of whom studied at the [[University of York]], became the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK. Upon confirmation, they were transferred from [[Hull University Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust|Hull University Teaching Hospital]] to a specialist isolation facility, a designated High Consequence Infectious Diseases Unit in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]'s [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]].<ref name=Ball31Jan2020>{{Cite news|last=Ball|first=Tom|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|title=Hunt for contacts of coronavirus-stricken pair in York|date=31 January 2020|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Wace|first2=Charlotte |issn=0140-0460|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204105559/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=Lancet14March2020>{{Cite journal|last=Moss|first=Peter|last2=Barlow|first2=Gavin|last3=Easom|first3=Nicholas|last4=Lillie|first4=Patrick|last5=Samson|first5=Anda|date=14 March 2020|title=Lessons for managing high-consequence infections from first COVID-19 cases in the UK|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930463-3|journal=The Lancet |volume=395|issue=10227|pages=e46|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30463-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32113507|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, an [[evacuations related to the COVID-19 pandemic|evacuation flight]] from Wuhan landed at [[RAF Brize Norton]] and the passengers, none of whom were showing symptoms, were taken to quarantine, in a staff residential block at [[Arrowe Park Hospital]] on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\">{{cite web |title=Britons in Wuhan to return home on Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131024212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There had previously been contention over whether the government should assist the repatriation of UK passport holders from the most affected areas in China, or restrict travel from affected regions altogether.<ref name=\"Standard27Jan2020\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|title=Ministers came under growing pressure today to evacuate Britons from the Chinese region shut down by the killer coronavirus.|date=27 January 2020|work=London Evening Standard|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222145256/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"McHutchon25Jan2020\">{{Cite news|last=McHutchon|first=David|url=https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|title=Too Weak, Too Slow: The UK Government's Dithering Response to the Wuhan Coronavirus Increases the Risk of Major Loss of Life|date=25 January 2020|work=|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222131735/https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|archive-date=22 February 2020|publisher=Technical Politics}}</ref> Some British nationals in Wuhan had been informed that they could be evacuated but any spouses or children with mainland Chinese passports could not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|title=British mum told to leave son behind in Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later overturned, but the delay meant that some people missed the flight.<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.BBC.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|title=British mum told to leave son behind in the city of Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\n=== February 2020 ===                  \nOn 6 February, a third confirmed case, a man who had recently travelled to Singapore prior to visiting a ski resort in the [[Haute-Savoie]], France, was reported in [[Brighton]]. He had been the source of infection to six of his relatives during a stay in France, before returning to the UK on 28 January.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|title=First British national to contract coronavirus had been in Singapore|first1=Sarah|last1=Boseley|first2=Denis|last2=Campbell|first3=Simon|last3=Murphy|date=6 February 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207020202/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|archive-date=7 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mohdin>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Kim Willsher Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|title=Coronavirus: British nine-year-old in hospital in France|date=8 February 2020|work=The Observer|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Madrid|first2=and Sam Jones in|issn=0029-7712|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226161959/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of his result, the UK's CMOs expanded the number of countries where a history of previous travel associated with flu-like symptoms \u2013 such as fever, cough and difficulty breathing \u2013 in the previous 14 days would require self-isolation and calling [[NHS 111]]. These countries included China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|title=COVID-19: guidance for staff in the transport sector|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220133756/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the total number of cases in the UK reached eight as four further cases were confirmed in people linked to the affected man from Brighton.<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|title=Coronavirus closes Brighton GP practice|date=11 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PHE10Feb2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|title=Chief Medical Officer for England announces four further coronavirus cases|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223522/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Globally, the virus had spread to 28 countries.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020>{{Cite journal|last=Mahase|first=Elisabeth|date=10 February 2020|title=Coronavirus: NHS staff get power to keep patients in isolation as UK declares \"serious threat\"|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|journal=[[British Medical Journal]]|volume=368|pages=m550|doi=10.1136/bmj.m550|issn=1756-1833|pmid=32041792|url-access=subscription|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191051/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the morning of 10 February, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], announced the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]], to give public health professionals \"strengthened powers\" to keep affected people and those believed to be a possible risk of having the virus, in isolation.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> That day, the [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], Merseyside, and the Kents Hill Park hotel and conference centre, [[Milton Keynes]] became designated isolation units.<ref name=gov.uk2Update>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004037/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|archive-date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> The following day, two of the eight confirmed cases in the UK were reported by BBC News to be [[general practitioners]].<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020/> A ninth case was confirmed [[COVID-19 pandemic in London|in London]] on 11 February.<ref name=BBC12Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|title=Ninth coronavirus case found in UK|date=12 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212193433/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n[[File:20200329 - Manchester - Short film about Coronavirus.webm|thumb|thumbtime=2:18|Lockdown in [[Manchester]]]]\n[[File:Depleted lavatory rolls during the 2020 Coronavirus outbreak, Morrisons, Wetherby (20th March 2020).jpg|thumb|right|The effects of [[panic buying]] in a [[Morrisons]] supermarket in [[Wetherby]], [[West Yorkshire]]]]\n[[File:Leeds Bradford Airport April 2020.jpg|thumb|right|Grounded aircraft at [[Leeds Bradford Airport]] in April 2020]]\nOn 1 March, further cases were reported in [[Greater Manchester]] of which some are believed to be contacts of the case in Surrey who had no history of travel abroad.<ref name=\"ITV1Mar2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|title=Twelve more people test positive for coronavirus bringing UK Covid-19 total to 35|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301144252/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews1March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|title=Coronavirus: Twelve more cases confirmed in England|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=bbc.co.uk/news|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, four further people in England tested positive. All four had recently travelled from Italy; they are from Hertfordshire, Devon and Kent.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The total number of UK cases was reported as having reached 40, though this was revised to 39 after additional testing.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM|date=2 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150239/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, when the total number of confirmed cases in the UK stood at 51, the UK Government unveiled their ''Coronavirus Action Plan'', which outlined what the UK had done already and what it planned to do next.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/>\n\nOn 2 March, also occurred the first corona-virus death in a care home, but at that time care home data were not yet published.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/30/five-already-dead-by-time-uk-reported-first-coronavirus-death</ref>\n\nOn 3 March occurred the first three hospital deaths in [[Nottingham]], [[Essex]] and [[Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, the COVID-19 Hospitalisation in England Surveillance System (CHESS) was initiated across all NHS Trusts.\n\nOn 17 March, [[NHS England]] announced that all non-urgent operations in England would be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317152225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on 17 March, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Rishi Sunak]] announced that \u00a3330bn would be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the 18 March over 750  patients were in hospital with COVID-19, this number rapidly grew and by 31 March the number of patients had increased by around 10,000.<ref name=26Adata>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-26-april-2020 retrieved 27 April 2020</ref> Admissions to hospital grew from around 600 a day on 20 March to more than 2,750 a day by 31 March.<ref name=30Aslides>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-30-april-2020</ref> Taken together, these data suggest that at least 4,500 patients were discharged from hospital in March. \nBy 31 March, England was the worst affected country in the United Kingdom with over 21,000 confirmed infections<ref>https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-another-367-die-in-england-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19-11966273</ref> and at least 3,850 death in hospital.\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n[[File:Abbey Inn April 2020.jpg|thumb|A closed [[public house]] offering a [[takeaway]] service|alt=]]\nOn 2 April the maximum number of hospital admissions was reached at more than 3,150 patients per day;<ref name=30Aslides /> the number of hospital deaths was around 600.<ref name=1Mdata>https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/covid-19-daily-deaths/ data on total number of deaths dated 1 May 2020</ref>\n\nBy 12 April the number of daily admissions with COVID-19 had reduced to less than 1,900<ref name=30Aslides /> and the number of patients in hospital peaked at around 17,150;<ref name=26Adata /> more than 680 hospital deaths were recorded.<ref name=1Mdata />\n\nIn the week of 18-24 April (week 17), ONS death registrations for England and Wales showed 19,643 occurred in hospital, 5,890 in care homes, 1,306 in private homes and 301 in hospices.<ref name=24AONS />\n\nOn 29 April the method of reporting deaths in England was changed.<ref>https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/about</ref> Data from three sources are now cross checked against the list of people who have had a diagnosis of COVID-19 confirmed by a Public Health England or NHS laboratory. The three sources are:\n\na) data supplied to NHS England by the Hospital Trusts,\n\nb) data from Public Health England Health Protection teams (mainly deaths not in hospitals),\n\nc) Information obtained by linking the Second Generation Surveillance System (SGSS) to the NHS Demographic Batch Service.\n\nAfter checking, the records are merged into one database and duplicates removed so there is no double counting.\n\nThe new method of counting deaths results in higher numbers than the previous method. On 29 April there were 19,740 deaths reported by NHS England. The new method identified 23,550 deaths of people who had a positive test result confirmed by a PHE or NHS laboratory.\n\nThe number of patients with COVID-19 in hospital steadily reduced until on 30 April it was less than 11,250;<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-1-may-2020</ref> at least 54,700 patients were admitted to hospital in April.<ref name=5Mayslides >https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-5-may-2020</ref> The total number of deaths in hospital during April exceeded 17,000;<ref name=26Adata /> these data suggest that there were around 26,400 patient discharges in April.\n\n=== May 2020 ===\nBy 3 May, daily admissions to hospital had further reduced to around 900, discharges continued to exceed admissions and thus the number of people in hospital was now less than 10,550.<ref name=5Mayslides />\n\nOn 7 May the number of people in hospital finally fell below 10,000, with every region showing a reduction from the previous day;<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-7-may-2020</ref> the total number of deaths in hospital since 1 March has grown to at least 22,432.<ref name=DM7>https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/covid-19-daily-deaths/ data on total number of deaths dated 7 May 2020</ref>\n\n==Hospital death statistics==\nPercentage deaths in hospital by age, up to 5 May.<ref name=DM7 />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Age range !! Pre-condition     !! No Known Pre-condition !! Female!! Male\n|-\n| 0-19 years || 0.04% || 0.01%||0.02%||0.03%\n|-\n| 20-39 years || 0.58% || 0.13%||0.31%||0.39%\n|-\n| 40-59 years || 7.1% || 0.94%||2.66%||5.32%\n|-\n| 60-79 years || 36.6% || 2.18%||13.06%||25.70%\n|-\n| 80+ years || 50.7% || 1.84%||22.24%||30.25%\n|}\n\n==ONS data==\n\n'All recorded deaths' and 'COVID-19 deaths' are the number of deaths recorded during each seven-day period and those where COVID-19 was mentioned on the death certificate. The total number of deaths will be greater as there is normally a delay between the day of death and when it is recorded. The five-year average is estimated from the data for England and Wales based on the percentage population living in England (94.69%).<ref name=20MONS >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending20march2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> Up to and including week ending 13 March, the number of deaths in England was around 445 fewer each week than the five-year average; the 'all recorded deaths' data for week ending 13 March is estimated from the deaths in England and Wales and all 5 COVID-19 deaths are attributed to England.<ref name=24AONS>https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending24april2020</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Week Ending !! All Recorded Deaths !! COVID-19 Deaths !! Other Deaths !! 5 Yr Average\n|-\n| 13 March || 10,434 || 5 || 10,429 || 10,610\n|-\n| 20 March<ref name=20MONS /> || 9,903 || 100 || 9,803 || 10,012\n|-\n| 27 March<ref name=27MONS >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending27march2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> || 10,412 || 515 || 9,897 || 9,592\n|-\n| 3 April<ref name=3APR >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending3april2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> || 15,443 || 3,330 || 12,113 || 9.758\n|-\n| 10 April<ref name=10APR >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending10april2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> || 17,563 || 5,899 || 11,664 || 9,961\n|-\n| 17 April<ref name=17APR >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending17april2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> || 21,157 || 8,335 || 12,822 || 9.940\n|-\n| 24 April<ref name=24AONS /> || 20,841 || 7,806 || 13,035 || 9,903\n|}\n\n==Comparison with other nations==\nDeaths per 100,000 population of all 4 countries of the UK, and others, for comparison (as at 7 May 2020).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country!! # of deaths!! Source !! Country<br />population<br />(in millions) || # of deaths per<br/>100,000<br/>population\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Georgia}} || 9 ||<ref>[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/georgia/ worldometers.info]; accessed 20 April 2020</ref>  || 3.7 || '''0.2'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|New Zealand}} || 21 ||<ref>[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/new-zealand/ worldometers.info]; accessed 20 April 2020</ref>  || 5.0 ||'''0.4'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Norway}} || 216 ||<ref>[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/new-zealand/ worldometers.info]; accessed 20 April 2020</ref>  || 5.3 ||'''3.9'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Slovenia}} || 93 ||<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1111779/coronavirus-death-rate-europe-by-country/ www.statista.com;] accessed 7 May 2020.</ref> || 2.0 ||'''4.7'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Austria}} || 606 ||<ref>[https://www.statista.com/statistics/1111779/coronavirus-death-rate-europe-by-country/ www.statista.com;] accessed 7 May 2020.</ref>  || 8.9 ||'''6.8'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Republic of Ireland}} || 1,339 ||<ref>[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/ireland/ www.worldometers.info;] accessed 20 April 2020.</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|title=39 more people die with Covid-19, 493 additional cases|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0419/1132482-update-covid-19-ireland/|date=2020-04-19|language=en}}</ref>  || 4.8 ||'''27.9'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Northern Ireland}} || 404 ||<ref>[https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-daily-data-for-scotland/ www.gov.scot;] accessed 7 May 2020.</ref> || 1.8 ||'''22.4'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Scotland}} || 1,703 ||<ref>[https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-daily-data-for-scotland/ www.gov.scot;] accessed 20 April 2020.</ref> || 5.4 ||'''31.5'''\n|- \n| {{Flagcountry|Wales}} || 1,044 ||<ref>[https://public.tableau.com/profile/public.health.wales.health.protection#!/vizhome/RapidCOVID-19virology-Public/Headlinesummary [[Public Health Wales]];] accessed 20 Ebrill 2020. </ref> || 3.2 ||'''32.6'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Italy}} || 29,684 ||<ref>[http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5351&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto www.salute.gov.it;] accessed 7 May 2020.</ref> <ref>[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/new-zealand/ worldometers.info]; accessed 20 April 2020</ref> || 60.3 || '''48.5'''\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|England}} || '''27,008''' ||<ref>[https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk ;] accessed 19 Ebrill 2020.</ref>|| '''53.0''' ||'''49.9'''\n|}\n\n==The military==\nThe coronavirus pandemic affected British military deployments at home and abroad. Training exercises, including those in Canada and Kenya, had to be cancelled to free up personnel for the COVID Support Force.<ref>{{cite news |title=10,000 extra troops to join British army's Covid support force |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132719/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The British training mission in Iraq, part of [[Operation Shader]], had to be down-scaled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Britain could see biggest mobilisation of military since Iraq war |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-britain-could-see-biggest-mobilisation-of-army-since-iraq-war-11963256 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> An air base supporting this military operation also confirmed nine cases of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Commander Of British Forces Cyprus Says Community Has 'Stood Tall' |url=https://www.forces.net/news/cyprus/coronavirus-commander-british-forces-cyprus-says-community-has-stood-tall |agency=forces.net |date=15 April 2020 |quote=More than 3,000 members of the UK military live and work in Cyprus, and so far, there have been 9{{nbsp}}mild cases of COVID-19 within the British bases.}}</ref> The British Army paused face-to-face recruitment and basic training operations, instead conducting them virtually.<ref>{{cite news |title=Army announcement |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/news-and-events/news/2020/03/army-announcement/ |agency=British Army |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Training locations, such as [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] and [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS ''Raleigh'']], had to adapt their passing out parades. Cadets involved were made to stand {{convert|2|m}} apart in combat dress and there were no spectators in the grandstands.<ref>{{cite news |title=New-Look Parade As Officer Cadets Pass Through Sandhurst During Pandemic |url=https://www.forces.net/news/new-look-parade-officer-cadets-pass-through-sandhurst-during-pandemic |agency=forces.net |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Recruits Finish Training Amid Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2020/march/27/20200327-hms-raleigh-finish-training |agency=Royal Navy |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Ceremonial duties, such as the [[Guard mounting|Changing of the Guard]] at [[Buckingham Palace]] and the Gun Salute for the [[Queen's Official Birthday]] were either scaled-down or cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Changing the Guard continues but without Music or Ceremony |url=https://www.army.mod.uk/news-and-events/news/2020/03/changing-the-guard-continues-but-without-music-or-ceremony/ |agency=British Army |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen's Birthday Gun Salutes Cancelled Over Coronavirus Restrictions |url=https://www.forces.net/news/queens-birthday-gun-salutes-cancelled-over-coronavirus-restrictions |agency=forces.net |date=18 April 2020}}</ref> The Royal Air Force suspended all displays of its teams and bands, with some replaced by virtual displays.<ref>{{cite news |title=Impact of Coronavirus (COVID-19) on RAF Display Teams in 2020 |url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/news/articles/impact-of-coronavirus-covid-19-on-raf-display-teams-in-2020/ |agency=Royal Air Force |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Battle Of Britain Commemorations To Take Place Online |url=https://www.forces.net/news/battle-britain-commemorations-take-place-online |agency=forces.net |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The British Army deployed two experts to [[NATO]] to help counter disinformation around the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Army Experts To Help NATO Combat Disinformation |url=https://www.forces.net/news/coronavirus-army-experts-help-nato-combat-disinformation |agency=forces.net |date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nElsewhere in defence, air shows, including the [[Royal International Air Tattoo]] at [[RAF Fairford]], were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Farnborough and RAF Fairford air shows cancelled |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-51978103 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Civilian airports, including [[Birmingham Airport]], were used to practice transferring Coronavirus patients to local hospitals via helicopter.<ref name=\"Irwin\">{{cite news |last1=Irwin |first1=David |title=Military helicopters training over airport amid Covid-19 crisis |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321180535/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Military on more manoeuvres around Birmingham Airport to transport coronavirus patients |url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Solihull Observer |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132723/https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several defence and aerospace companies contributed to the national effort to produce more ventilators.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Aerospace companies to lead national ventilator effort |url=https://www.janes.com/article/94999/covid-19-aerospace-companies-to-lead-national-ventilator-effort |agency=Janes |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> [[BAE Systems]], the country's largest defence company, also loaned its [[Warton Aerodrome]] site to be used as a temporary morgue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Every known detail on morgue to be set up at BAE Systems in Warton |url=https://www.lancs.live/news/lancashire-news/every-known-detail-morgue-set-18066310 |agency=lancs.live |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Government's defence and security review, named the [[Strategic Defence and Security Review 2020|Integrated Review]], was delayed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Major Defence And Security Review Paused Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.forces.net/news/major-defence-and-security-review-paused-over-coronavirus |agency=forces.net |date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe armed forces assisted in the transportation of coronavirus patients in some of the country's remotest regions, such as [[Shetland]] and the [[Isles of Scilly]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Military called in to fly Covid-19 patient to intensive care |url=https://www.shetnews.co.uk/2020/03/22/military-called-in-to-fly-covid-19-patient-to-intensive-care/ |agency=shetnews.co.uk |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Headquarters Standing Joint Command (HQ SJC): Coordinating the military contribution to the UK's resilience operations |url=https://medium.com/@DefenceHQ/headquarters-standing-joint-command-hq-sjc-coordinating-the-military-contribution-to-the-uks-99b447414235 |agency=medium.com |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March 2020, [[Joint Helicopter Command]] began assisting the coronavirus relief effort by transporting people and supplies. Helicopters were based at [[RAF Leeming]] to cover Northern England and Scotland, whilst helicopters based at [[RAF Benson]], [[RAF Odiham]] and [[RNAS Yeovilton (HMS Heron)|RNAS Yeovilton]] supported the Midlands and Southern England.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Measures To Support Battle Against Coronavirus In Scotland |url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/coronavirus/new-measures-to-support-battle-against-coronavirus-in-scotland/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=raf.mod.uk |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, the armed forces helped plan and construct a field hospital at the [[ExCeL London]] conference centre, named [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]]. Further [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|critical care field hospitals]] were later built with military assistance in Birmingham, Manchester, Harrogate, Bristol, Exeter, Washington and Glasgow. These hospitals were staffed by military medics, alongside the NHS.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Army Supports Glasgow SEC Centre's Conversion Into Temporary Hospital |url=https://www.forces.net/news/coronavirus-army-support-glasgow-secs-conversion-temporary-hospital |agency=forces.net |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in Northern Ireland]]\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland]]\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in Wales]]\n* [[COVID-19 pandemic in London]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19 pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in England| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in England]]\n[[Category:Health in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in England}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = COVID-19 pandemic in England\n| image           = Waitrose Supermarket - King's Road, London SW3 UK COVID-19 Lock down.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             =\n| caption         = Queue at a supermarket in London, each customer 2 meters from the next person; April 2020\n| map1 = COVID-19 outbreak England per capita cases map.svg\n| image2          = \n| places =\n| legend1 = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents by upper tier local authority area\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[England]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date =\n| origin = [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 131,932 (as of 7 May)<ref name=ArcGISUK>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the UK |website=coronavirus.data.gov.uk |access-date=1 May 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"theg_Coro\">{{Cite web| title = Coronavirus UK: how many confirmed cases are in your area?| last = Guti\u00e9rrez | first = Pablo| work = the Guardian| date = 27 March 2020| access-date = 27 March 2020| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/coronavirus-uk-how-many-confirmed-cases-are-in-your-area}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 27,432 (as of 7 May)<ref name=ArcGISUK/><ref name=\"bbc._Howm\">{{Cite web| title = How many confirmed cases are there in your area?| author = | work = BBC News| date = 2020-03-27| access-date = 27 March 2020| url = https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51768274}}</ref>\n| total_ili =\n| website = [https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus in England]\n}}\nThe [[COVID-19 pandemic]] was first confirmed to have spread to [[England]] with two cases among Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]] on 31 January 2020. The two main public bodies responsible for health in England are [[NHS England]] and [[Public Health England]]. NHS England oversees the budget, planning, delivery and day-to-day operation of the commissioning side of the NHS in England while PHE's mission is \"to protect and improve the nation\u2019s health and to address inequalities\".\n\nBy 7 May 2020, 27,008 people had died and there were 118,343 positive cases in England.<ref name=ArcGISUK/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== January 2020 ===\nOn 31 January, two members of a family of Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]], one of whom studied at the [[University of York]], became the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK. Upon confirmation, they were transferred from [[Hull University Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust|Hull University Teaching Hospital]] to a specialist isolation facility, a designated High Consequence Infectious Diseases Unit in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]'s [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]].<ref name=Ball31Jan2020>{{Cite news|last=Ball|first=Tom|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|title=Hunt for contacts of coronavirus-stricken pair in York|date=31 January 2020|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Wace|first2=Charlotte |issn=0140-0460|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204105559/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=Lancet14March2020>{{Cite journal|last=Moss|first=Peter|last2=Barlow|first2=Gavin|last3=Easom|first3=Nicholas|last4=Lillie|first4=Patrick|last5=Samson|first5=Anda|date=14 March 2020|title=Lessons for managing high-consequence infections from first COVID-19 cases in the UK|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930463-3|journal=The Lancet |volume=395|issue=10227|pages=e46|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30463-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=32113507|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, an [[evacuations related to the COVID-19 pandemic|evacuation flight]] from Wuhan landed at [[RAF Brize Norton]] and the passengers, none of whom were showing symptoms, were taken to quarantine, in a staff residential block at [[Arrowe Park Hospital]] on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\">{{cite web |title=Britons in Wuhan to return home on Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131024212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There had previously been contention over whether the government should assist the repatriation of UK passport holders from the most affected areas in China, or restrict travel from affected regions altogether.<ref name=\"Standard27Jan2020\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|title=Ministers came under growing pressure today to evacuate Britons from the Chinese region shut down by the killer coronavirus.|date=27 January 2020|work=London Evening Standard|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222145256/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"McHutchon25Jan2020\">{{Cite news|last=McHutchon|first=David|url=https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|title=Too Weak, Too Slow: The UK Government's Dithering Response to the Wuhan Coronavirus Increases the Risk of Major Loss of Life|date=25 January 2020|work=|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222131735/https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|archive-date=22 February 2020|publisher=Technical Politics}}</ref> Some British nationals in Wuhan had been informed that they could be evacuated but any spouses or children with mainland Chinese passports could not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|title=British mum told to leave son behind in Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later overturned, but the delay meant that some people missed the flight.<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.BBC.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|title=British mum told to leave son behind in the city of Wuhan|date=30 January 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\n=== February 2020 ===                  \nOn 6 February, a third confirmed case, a man who had recently travelled to Singapore prior to visiting a ski resort in the [[Haute-Savoie]], France, was reported in [[Brighton]]. He had been the source of infection to six of his relatives during a stay in France, before returning to the UK on 28 January.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|title=First British national to contract coronavirus had been in Singapore|first1=Sarah|last1=Boseley|first2=Denis|last2=Campbell|first3=Simon|last3=Murphy|date=6 February 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207020202/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|archive-date=7 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mohdin>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Kim Willsher Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|title=Coronavirus: British nine-year-old in hospital in France|date=8 February 2020|work=The Observer|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Madrid|first2=and Sam Jones in|issn=0029-7712|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226161959/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of his result, the UK's CMOs expanded the number of countries where a history of previous travel associated with flu-like symptoms \u2013 such as fever, cough and difficulty breathing \u2013 in the previous 14 days would require self-isolation and calling [[NHS 111]]. These countries included China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|title=COVID-19: guidance for staff in the transport sector|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220133756/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the total number of cases in the UK reached eight as four further cases were confirmed in people linked to the affected man from Brighton.<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|title=Coronavirus closes Brighton GP practice|date=11 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PHE10Feb2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|title=Chief Medical Officer for England announces four further coronavirus cases|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223522/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Globally, the virus had spread to 28 countries.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020>{{Cite journal|last=Mahase|first=Elisabeth|date=10 February 2020|title=Coronavirus: NHS staff get power to keep patients in isolation as UK declares \"serious threat\"|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|journal=[[British Medical Journal]]|volume=368|pages=m550|doi=10.1136/bmj.m550|issn=1756-1833|pmid=32041792|url-access=subscription|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191051/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the morning of 10 February, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], announced the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]], to give public health professionals \"strengthened powers\" to keep affected people and those believed to be a possible risk of having the virus, in isolation.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> That day, the [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], Merseyside, and the Kents Hill Park hotel and conference centre, [[Milton Keynes]] became designated isolation units.<ref name=gov.uk2Update>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004037/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|archive-date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> The following day, two of the eight confirmed cases in the UK were reported by BBC News to be [[general practitioners]].<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020/> A ninth case was confirmed [[COVID-19 pandemic in London|in London]] on 11 February.<ref name=BBC12Feb2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|title=Ninth coronavirus case found in UK|date=12 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212193433/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n[[File:20200329 - Manchester - Short film about Coronavirus.webm|thumb|thumbtime=2:18|Lockdown in [[Manchester]]]]\n[[File:Depleted lavatory rolls during the 2020 Coronavirus outbreak, Morrisons, Wetherby (20th March 2020).jpg|thumb|right|The effects of [[panic buying]] in a [[Morrisons]] supermarket in [[Wetherby]], [[West Yorkshire]]]]\n[[File:Leeds Bradford Airport April 2020.jpg|thumb|right|Grounded aircraft at [[Leeds Bradford Airport]] in April 2020]]\nOn 1 March, further cases were reported in [[Greater Manchester]] of which some are believed to be contacts of the case in Surrey who had no history of travel abroad.<ref name=\"ITV1Mar2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|title=Twelve more people test positive for coronavirus bringing UK Covid-19 total to 35|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301144252/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews1March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|title=Coronavirus: Twelve more cases confirmed in England|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=bbc.co.uk/news|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, four further people in England tested positive. All four had recently travelled from Italy; they are from Hertfordshire, Devon and Kent.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The total number of UK cases was reported as having reached 40, though this was revised to 39 after additional testing.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM|date=2 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150239/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, when the total number of confirmed cases in the UK stood at 51, the UK Government unveiled their ''Coronavirus Action Plan'', which outlined what the UK had done already and what it planned to do next.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/>\n\nOn 2 March, also occurred the first corona-virus death in a care home, but at that time care home data were not yet published.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/30/five-already-dead-by-time-uk-reported-first-coronavirus-death</ref>\n\nOn 3 March occurred the first three hospital deaths in [[Nottingham]], [[Essex]] and [[Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, the COVID-19 Hospitalisation in England Surveillance System (CHESS) was initiated across all NHS Trusts.\n\nOn 17 March, [[NHS England]] announced that all non-urgent operations in England would be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317152225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on 17 March, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Rishi Sunak]] announced that \u00a3330bn would be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the 18 March over 750  patients were in hospital with COVID-19, this number rapidly grew and by 31 March the number of patients had increased by around 10,000.<ref name=26Adata>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-26-april-2020 retrieved 27 April 2020</ref> Admissions to hospital grew from around 600 a day on 20 March to more than 2,750 a day by 31 March.<ref name=30Aslides>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-30-april-2020</ref> Taken together, these data suggest that at least 4,500 patients were discharged from hospital in March. \nBy 31 March, England was the worst affected country in the United Kingdom with over 21,000 confirmed infections<ref>https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-another-367-die-in-england-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19-11966273</ref> and at least 3,850 death in hospital.\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n[[File:Abbey Inn April 2020.jpg|thumb|A closed [[public house]] offering a [[takeaway]] service|alt=]]\nOn 2 April the maximum number of hospital admissions was reached at more than 3,150 patients per day;<ref name=30Aslides /> the number of hospital deaths was around 600.<ref name=1Mdata>https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/covid-19-daily-deaths/ data on total number of deaths dated 1 May 2020</ref>\n\nBy 12 April the number of daily admissions with COVID-19 had reduced to less than 1900<ref name=30Aslides /> and the number of patients in hospital peaked at around 17,150;<ref name=26Adata /> more than 680 hospital deaths were recorded.<ref name=1Mdata />\n\nIn the week 18-24 April (Week 17) ONS death registrations for England and Wales showed 19,643 occurred in hospital, 5,890 in care homes, 1306 in private homes and 301 in hospices<ref name=24AONS />.\n\nOn 29 April the method of reporting deaths in England was changed,.<ref>https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/about</ref> Data from three sources are now cross checked against the list of people who have had a diagnosis of COVID-19 confirmed by a Public Health England or NHS laboratory. The three sources are:\n\na) Data supplied to NHS England by the Hospital Trusts,\n\nb) Data from Public Health England Health Protection Teams(mainly deaths not in hospitals),\n\nc) Information obtained by linking the Second Generation Surveillance System (SGSS) to the NHS Demographic Batch Service.\n\nAfter checking, the records are merged into one database and duplicates removed so there is no double counting.\n\nThe new method of counting deaths results in higher numbers than the previous method. On 29 April 2020 there were 19,740 deaths reported by NHS England. The new method identified 23,550 deaths of people who had a positive test result confirmed by a PHE or NHS laboratory.\n\nThe number of patients with COVID-19 in hospital steadily reduced until on 30 April it was less than 11,250;<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-1-may-2020</ref> at least 54,700 patients were admitted to hospital in April.<ref name=5Mayslides >https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-5-may-2020</ref> The total number of deaths in hospital during April exceeded 17,000;<ref name=26Adata /> these data suggest that there were around 26,400 patient discharges in April.\n\n=== May 2020 ===\nBy 3 May, daily admissions to hospital had further reduced to around 900, discharges continued to exceed admissions and thus the number of people in hospital was now less than 10,550.<ref name=5Mayslides />\n\nOn 7 May the number of people in hospital finally fell below 10,000, with every region showing a reduction from the previous day;<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/slides-and-datasets-to-accompany-coronavirus-press-conference-7-may-2020</ref> the total number of deaths in hospital since 1 March has grown to at least 22,432.<ref name=DM7>https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/covid-19-daily-deaths/ data on total number of deaths dated 7 May 2020</ref>\n\n==Hospital death statistics==\nPercentage deaths in hospital by age, up to 5 May.<ref name=DM7 />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Age range !! Pre-condition     !! No Known Pre-condition !! Female!! Male\n|-\n| 0-19 years || 0.04% || 0.01%||0.02%||0.03%\n|-\n| 20-39 years || 0.58% || 0.13%||0.31%||0.39%\n|-\n| 40-59 years || 7.1% || 0.94%||2.66%||5.32%\n|-\n| 60-79 years || 36.6% || 2.18%||13.06%||25.70%\n|-\n| 80+ years || 50.7% || 1.84%||22.24%||30.25%\n|}\n\n==ONS data==\n\n'All recorded deaths' and 'COVID-19 deaths' are the number of deaths recorded during each seven-day period and those where COVID-19 was mentioned on the death certificate. The total number of deaths will be greater as there is normally a delay between the day of death and when it is recorded. The five-year average is estimated from the data for England and Wales based on the percentage population living in England (94.69%).<ref name=20MONS >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending20march2020 data set used 'Deaths by Region'</ref> Up to and including week ending 13 March, the number of deaths in England was around 445 fewer each week than the five-year average; the 'all recorded deaths' data for week ending 13 March is estimated from the deaths in England and Wales and all 5 COVID-19 deaths are attributed to England.<ref name=24AONS>https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending24april2020</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Week Ending !! All Recorded Deaths !! COVID-19 Deaths !! Other Deaths !! 5 Yr Average\n|-\n| 13 March || 10,434 || 5 || 10,429 || 10,610\n|-\n| 20 March<ref name=20MONS /> || 9,903 || 100 || 9,803 || 10,012\n|-\n| 27 March<ref name=27MONS >https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending27march2020 data set used 'Deaths by Reg